sec.p:
The Ni/MH battery is a reversible electrochemical device that allows to store and produce electrical energy by means of electrochemical reactions. These reactions occur at the surface of active materials (or electrodes) in contact with an alkaline electrolyte, Fig. 1. The active material used in the positive electrode (cathode) of these batteries is the Ni(OH)2 compound. During charge, this active material experiences +2/+3 oxidation state change promoted by the electrochemical reaction [10, 11]. The following half-cell electrochemical reaction takes place at the cathode:Fig. 1
Schematic diagram of the operation of a Ni/MH cell1xNiOH2+OH-↔NiOOH+xH2O+xe-forward: charge;reverse: discharge\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$x{\text{Ni}}\left( {\text{OH}} \right)_{ 2} + {\text{OH}}^{ - } \leftrightarrow {\text{NiOOH}} + x{\text{H}}_{ 2} {\text{O}} + x{\text{e}}^{ - } \left( {{\text{forward: charge}};{\text{ reverse: discharge}}} \right)$$\end{document}

As a result, protons released from the active material move to its surface and recombine with hydroxide ions in the electrolyte. On the other hand, in the negative electrode (anode), the active material is a special kind of alloy known as hydrogen storage alloy (or metal hydride (MH) alloy) that is capable to store hydrogen in a reversible way [12]. During charge, the applied voltage splits water molecules into hydroxide ions and hydrogen protons. As a result, the reduction of water allows hydrogen protons to be in contact with the hydrogen storage alloy. Protons enter then into the bulk of the alloy to form a MH driven by the voltage and diffusion caused by the concentration gradient [12, 13]. The half-cell electrochemical reaction at the anode is:2M+xH2O+xe-↔MHx+HO-forward: charge;reverse: discharge\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{M}} + x{\text{H}}_{ 2} {\text{O}} + x{\text{e}}^{ - } \leftrightarrow {\text{MH}}_{x} + {\text{HO}}^{ - } \left( {{\text{forward: charge}};{\text{ reverse: discharge}}} \right)$$\end{document}

Therefore, the overall reaction for the battery is:3xNiOHx+M↔xNiOOH+MHxforward: charge;reverse: discharge\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$x{\text{Ni}}\left( {\text{OH}} \right)_{x} + {\text{M}} \leftrightarrow x{\text{NiOOH}} + {\text{MH}}_{x} \left( {{\text{forward: charge}};{\text{ reverse: discharge}}} \right)$$\end{document}

The electrochemical behavior of the RE-perovskite-type electrodes reported on the work of Deng et al. [59] can be attributed to the mechanisms for hydrogen absorption/desorption in RE-perovskite-type materials. The hydrogen absorption mechanism in RE-perovskite-type oxides is similar to that presented before for intermetallic alloys, where the storage of hydrogen atoms is given by the reduction of water at the interface electrolyte/active material. Hydrogen atoms are then captured within the structure of the RE-perovskite-type oxide to form a solid solution, i.e., a hydride compound [27, 59, 77]. Accordingly, the half-cell electrochemical reaction at the RE-perovskite-type negative electrode is:4ABO3+xH2O+xe-↔AB1-xBxO3Hx+xHO-forward: charge;reverse: discharge\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{ABO}}_{ 3} + x{\text{H}}_{ 2} {\text{O}} + x{\text{e}}^{ - } \leftrightarrow {\text{AB}}_{ 1- x} {\text{B}}_{x} {\text{O}}_{ 3} {\text{H}}_{x} + x{\text{HO}}^{ - } \left( {{\text{forward: charge}};{\text{ reverse: discharge}}} \right)$$\end{document}

Thus, the overall reaction for the Ni/MH battery can be re-defined as follows:5xNiOHx+ABO3↔xNiOOH+AB1-xBxO3Hxforward:charge;reverse:discharge\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
